what is internet ?
- global network of interconnected computers
- that enables the exchange of information and communication between devices
- allow devices to communicate with each other
and access a wide range of resources, including websites, online
applications, and online services.
How domain works ?
A domain is a unique name that identifies a website or a group of websites on the Internet.
A domain name consists of a series of characters that are used to identify a specific website or group of websites.
For example, the domain name "google.com" identifies the website of the search engine company Google.
There are a number of different types of domains that can be used to identify websites on the Internet.
The most common type of domain is a top-level domain (TLD), which is the part of the domain name that appears after the final dot.
Some examples of TLDs include .com, .net, .org, and .edu.
Other types of domains include country code top-level domains (ccTLDs),
which are used to identify websites in specific countries, and generic top-level domains (gTLDs),
which are used to identify websites in specific industries or categories.
In order to use a domain name, you must register it with a domain registrar,
which is a company that manages the allocation of domain names.
Once you have registered a domain name, you can use it to create a website or use it as part of an email address.
Role of DNS ?
- The Domain Name System (DNS) is a system that translates domain names into numerical IP addresses that computers can understand
and use to communicate with each other.
- When you type a domain name into your web browser, the DNS servers that your computer is connected to will translate that domain
name into the corresponding IP address for the website you are trying to access.
- DNS servers work like a phone book for the Internet.
- Just as a phone book contains a list of phone numbers and names, DNS servers contain a list of IP addresses and domain names.
When you type a domain name into your web browser, the DNS server looks up the corresponding IP address and directs your computer
to the correct website.
- The DNS system is an essential part of the Internet, as it allows users to access websites using easy-to-remember domain names
instead of having to remember complex numerical IP addresses. It also allows websites to move to different servers or hosting providers
without having to change their domain names.
DNS RESOLVER ?
- A DNS resolver is a computer program or a network service that helps to resolve domain names into numerical IP addresses.
- When you type a domain name into your web browser, the DNS resolver on your computer will send a request to a DNS server to
look up the corre sponding IP address for that domain name.
- The DNS resolver first checks its cache to see if it has recently resolved the same domain name.
- If it has, it will return the IP address from its cache to the requesting program,
which can then use the IP address to access the website. If the DNS resolver does not have the IP address in its cache,
it will forward the request to a DNS server.
- The DNS server will then search its database for the IP address associated with the domain name. If the DNS server finds the IP address,
it will return it to the DNS resolver, which will then pass it on to the requesting program.
- If the DNS server does not have the IP address in its database, it will forward the request to other DNS servers in an attempt to find the IP address.
This process is known as recursive resolution.
- Once the DNS resolver has received the IP address for the domain name, it will add the domain name and IP address to its cache
so that it can quickly resolve the same domain name in the future.

Ip Address
An IP address (Internet Protocol address) is a numerical label assigned to each device connected to a
computer network that uses the Internet Protocol for communication.
An IP address serves two main functions: host or network interface identification and location addressing.
IP addresses are made up of four numbers separated by periods. Each number can be between 0 and 255.
For example, an IP address might look like this: 192.168.0.1.
IP addresses are used to identify devices on a network and to route traffic between networks. When you access a
website or send an email, your device sends a request to the network, which uses the IP address to locate the
destination device and route the request to it. The destination device then sends a response back to your device
through the same process.
Breakdown of An Sample IP !
- The first number, 192, represents the network that the device is a part of.
In this case, the device is on a private network, as designated by the 192.168 prefix.
- The next number, 168, represents the subnet within the network. This number is used to identify a
group of devices within the network and can be used to divide the network into smaller, more manageable segments.
- The third number, 0, represents the specific subnet within the network. This number is used to further divide
the network into smaller seg- ments.
- The fourth number, 1, represents the specific device on the network.
This number is used to identify the device and distinguish it from other devices on the network.
HTTP
- HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) is a protocol for transmitting data across the Internet.
It is the foundation of data communication on the World Wide Web and is used to transmit data
between a web server and a web browser.
- When you enter a URL into your web browser, your computer sends an HTTP request to the web server
associated with that URL. The web server then processes the request and sends back an HTTP response,
which includes the requested data (such as a web page or an image) as well as information about how
to display the data (such as the type of data and the encoding used).
- HTTP is a stateless protocol, which means that it does not maintain a connection between the client
and the server after the data has been transmitted. This allows multiple clients to access the server
at the same time without interference.
- HTTP has evolved over time and there are now several versions of the protocol, including HTTP/1.0,
HTTP/1.1, and HTTP/2. Each version includes various improvements and changes to the protocol to
improve performance and security.
PORTS
- In computer networking, a port is a logical connection point for sending or receiving data on a computer.
When data is transmitted over the Internet or other networks,
it is divided into small packets and each packet is sent to its destination with the help of a port number.
- In computer networking, a port is a logical connection point for sending or receiving data on a computer.
When data is transmitted over the Internet or other networks,
it is divided into small packets and each packet is sent to its destination with the help of a port number.
Ports are used to distinguish different types of traffic on a computer and to route data to the appropriate
application or service. For example, when you access a website, your web browser sends an HTTP request to the
web server using port 80. When you send an email, your email client sends the email to the email server using
port 25.
- There are two types of ports: physical ports and virtual ports.
- Physical ports are the actual connectors on a device, such as the ports on the back of your router or the ports on
the side of your laptop.
- Virtual ports are software-defined ports that are used by applications and services to communicate with each other.
- Each port has a unique number, ranging from 0 to 65535, that is used to identify the port and the type of traffic
that it handles. Some common port numbers include 80 (HTTP), 25 (SMTP), and 53 (DNS).
HTTPS METHODS
In HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol), there are several request methods that a client (such as a web browser) can use
when making a request to a server.
These request methods indicate the type of action that the client wishes to take. Here are the most common HTTP
request methods:
GET
This request method is used to retrieve data from the server.
It is the most common request method, and is used when you visit a website or click on a link.
HEAD
This request method is similar to GET, but it only retrieves the headers of the response,
not the actual data. It is often used to check if a resource is available or to check
its modification date.
POST
This request method is used to send data to the server,
usually to create or update a resource. It is often used when you submit a form on a website.
PUT
This request method is used to update a resource on the server. It is similar to POST,
but the request specifically indicates that the resource should be updated, rather than
created if it doesn't exist.
DELETE
This request method is used to delete a resource on the server.
* There are also several other HTTP request methods, such as PATCH, OPTIONS, and TRACE, but they are less commonly used.
HTTPS REQUEST STATUS CODE
HTTP status codes are three-digit codes that are returned by a server in response to a client's request.
They indicate the status of the request, and can help you understand what happened when the server received the request.
Here are some common HTTP status codes:
- 2xx Success: This range of status codes indicates that the request was successful.
For example, a 200 OK status code indicates that the request was successful and the requested information was returned in the response.
- 3xx Redirection: This range of status codes indicates that the client must take additional action in order to complete the request.
For example, a 301 Moved Permanently status code indicates that the requested resource has been moved to a new location, and the client
should use the new location to make future requests.
- 4xx Client Error: This range of status codes indicates that there was an error with the request made by the client.
For example, a 404 Not Found status code indicates that the server could not find the requested resource.
- 5xx Server Error: This range of status codes indicates that there was an error on the server while processing the request.
For example, a 500 Internal Server Error status code indicates that the server encountered an unexpected condition that prevented it from
fulfilling the request.
** There are many other HTTP status codes, and a full list can be found in the HTTP specification.
